{{about|the elder daughter of George W. Bush|her namesake grandmother, mother of George W. Bush and wife of George H. W. Bush|Barbara Bush}} {{pp-pc1}} {{Infobox person |name = Barbara Bush |image = BBush at wedding.jpg |caption = Bush in May 2008 |birth_name = Barbara Pierce Bush |birth_date = {{birth date and age |1981|11|25}} |birth_place = [[Dallas, Texas]] |residence = [[New York City]] |alma_mater = [[Yale University]] |occupation = Health care activist |party = [[Independent voter|Independent]] |spouse = {{marriage|Craig Coyne|October 7, 2018}} |parents = {{plain list| * [[George W. Bush]] * [[Laura Bush]] }} |relations = [[Jenna Bush Hager]] <small>(twin sister)</small> |family = [[Bush family|Bush]] }}
'''Barbara Pierce Bush''' (born November 25, 1981) is one of the [[sororal twin|fraternal twin]] daughters (the other is [[Jenna Bush Hager]]) of the 43rd [[U.S. President]] [[George W. Bush]] and former [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Laura Bush]]. She is also a granddaughter of the 41st U.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]], and his wife, [[Barbara Bush]], after whom she was named. On October 7, 2018, she married actor and screen writer Craig Coyne.
==Early life== [[Image:Bush daughters.png|thumb|left|[[Jenna Bush Hager|Jenna]] and Barbara Bush (right) in 1990 with their parents [[George W. Bush]] and [[Laura Bush]]]]
Barbara Pierce Bush was born at [[Baylor University Medical Center]] in [[Dallas, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|pmc=1200659|title=Neonatal care at Baylor University Medical Center: You've come a long way, baby!|date=July 17, 2004|last=Whitfield|first=Jonathan M.|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> When the family lived in the [[Preston Hollow, Dallas, Texas|Preston Hollow]] section of Dallas, she and her twin sister, [[Jenna Bush Hager|Jenna]], attended [[Preston Hollow Elementary School]]; Laura Bush served on Preston Hollow's Parent-Teacher Association at that time.<ref>{{cite news|last=Pulle|first=Matt|title=Split Decision|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/news/split-decision-6377250|newspaper=[[Dallas Observer]]|date=January 11, 2007|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Later, Barbara and Jenna attended [[The Hockaday School]] in Dallas. When her father became [[Governor of Texas]] in 1994, Barbara attended [[St. Andrew's Episcopal School (Texas)|St. Andrew's Episcopal School]] in [[Austin, Texas]]. She began [[Austin High School (Austin, Texas)|Austin High School]] in 1996, graduating with the class of 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://quest.cjonline.com/stories/040400/gen_private.shtml|title=Bush used private school option|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=April 4, 2000|accessdate=August 22, 2006|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805010842/http://quest.cjonline.com/stories/040400/gen_private.shtml|archivedate=August 5, 2009|df=}}</ref>
Bush attended [[Yale University]], where she was a member of [[Kappa Alpha Theta]]. She lives in the [[Greenwich Village]] neighborhood of [[New York City]].<ref name=nypost>{{cite news|date=November 9, 2006|work=[[New York Post]] Online Edition|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/11092006/gossip/pagesix/secure_location_pagesix_.htm|title=Secure location|accessdate=January 24, 2007 |deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070121114302/http://www.nypost.com/seven/11092006/gossip/pagesix/secure_location_pagesix_.htm|archivedate=January 21, 2007|df=}}</ref>
==Career== She worked for the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum]], a subsidiary of the [[Smithsonian Institution]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Argetsinger|first1=Amy|first2=Roxanne|last2=Roberts|url=http://legacy.sandiegouniontribune.com/uniontrib/20060703/news_lz1n3nowread.html|title=First Twin Jenna Bush may leave D.C. social scene|newspaper=[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=July 3, 2006|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/books/news/2007-03-05-jenna-bush_N.htm/|last=Minzesheimer|first=Bob|title=Jenna Bush embarks on book 'Journey'|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=March 6, 2007|accessdate= April 21, 2018}}</ref> Previously, she had been working with [[AIDS]] patients in [[Africa]]: [[Tanzania]], [[South Africa]], and [[Botswana]], among other places, through a program sponsored by the [[Houston, Texas|Houston]]-based [[Baylor College of Medicine]]'s International Pediatrics AIDS Initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50537-2004May23.html|title=Telephoto Finish: The Bush Twins Graduate From College, and Private Life|work=The Washington Post|date=May 24, 2004|author=Dana Milbank|page=C01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=68&art_id=qw1121318105164R131|title=Bush twins not deterred by shutterbugs|date=July 14, 2005|author=Jennifer Loven|work=Independent Online (Pty) Ltd. "IOL"|accessdate=January 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060615021453/http://www.int.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1|archive-date=2006-06-15|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/africa/articles/2005/07/06/bush_daughter_is_said_to_volunteer_in_s_africa/?page=full|title=Bush daughter is said to volunteer in S. Africa|author=John Donnelly|date=July 6, 2005|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=May 25, 2004|url=https://khn.org/morning-breakout/dr00023889/|work=Kaiser Daily HIV/AIDS Report|title=Bush's Daughter to Intern for Baylor College of Medicine's International Pediatric AIDS Initiative Clinics in Africa|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>
===Global Health Corps=== She is the co-founder and president of a public health-focused nonprofit, [[Global Health Corps]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonscene.thehill.com/in-the-know/36-news/3337-george-bushs-daughter-barbara-to-discuss-global-health-at-the-national-press-club|title=In The Know|newspaper=The Hill|date=November 27, 2013|accessdate=December 4, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100412225446/http://washingtonscene.thehill.com/in-the-know/36-news/3337-george-bushs-daughter-barbara-to-discuss-global-health-at-the-national-press-club|archivedate=April 12, 2010|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> Global Health Corps provides opportunities for young professionals from diverse backgrounds to work on the front lines of the fight for global [[health equity]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission & Vision|url=http://ghcorps.org/why-were-here/mission-vision/|publisher=[[Global Health Corps]]|accessdate=July 23, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121202073159/http://ghcorps.org/why-were-here/mission-vision/|archivedate=December 2, 2012|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> In 2009, Global Health Corps won a Draper Richards Foundation Fellowship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/globalhealth.html|title=www.draperrichards.org|publisher=[[Draper Richards Kaplan Foundation]] |accessdate=July 23, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103015947/http://www.draperrichards.org/fellows/globalhealth.html|archivedate=January 3, 2012}}</ref> Bush was also chosen as one of the 14 speakers selected from an applicant pool of 1,500 to speak at the [[TED (conference)|TEDx Brooklyn]] event in December 2010, where she spoke about Global Health Corps.<ref>[https://blog.ted.com/7-tedxtalks-from-women-making-change-to-get-you-ready-for-tedxwomen/ 7 TEDxTalks from women making change to get you ready for TEDxWomen] [[TED (conference)|TED]] blog, November 30, 2012, Retrieved April 21, 2018.</ref>
==Political activity== [[File:Barbara Pierce Bush 2004 RNC P42830-094.jpg|thumb|left|Bush speaking at the 2004 Republican National Convention]] [[Image:Laura and Barbara Bush meet Pope Benedict XVI.jpg|right|thumb|Barbara Bush (second from the left), and her mother, former [[First Lady of the United States]] Laura Bush at the Vatican with [[Pope Benedict XVI]]]] In 2011, Bush released a video with the [[Human Rights Campaign]], the nation's largest lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) civil rights organization, calling on [[New York State]] to legalize [[same-sex marriage]].<ref>[//www.youtube.com/watch?v=-iKqr230U9M Barbara Bush for HRC's NYers for Marriage Equality], HRCMedia on [[YouTube]]</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Barbaro|first=Michael|date=January 31, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/01/us/politics/01bush.html?_r=1&hpw|title=Bush's Daughter, in a Break, Endorses Gay Marriage |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> "'I am Barbara Bush, and I am a New Yorker for marriage equality,' she says in the brief message, sponsored by an advocacy group. 'New York is about fairness and equality. And everyone should have the right to marry the person that they love.'"<ref name=NYT/> Bush joined other children of prominent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politicians—including [[Meghan McCain]] and [[Mary Cheney]]—in endorsing gay marriage.<ref name=NYT/>
Bush's graduation from Yale in May 2004 was given heavy media coverage. She and Jenna made several media appearances that summer prior to the [[2004 US Presidential election|2004 U.S. Presidential election]], including giving a speech to the [[2004 Republican National Convention|Republican Convention]] on August 31.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A51005-2004Aug31.html|work=The Washington Post|title=Remarks by Barbara and Jenna Bush to the 2004 Republican National Convention|date=August 31, 2004|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> The two took turns traveling to [[swing state]]s with their father and also gave a seven-page interview and photo shoot in [[Vogue magazine|''Vogue'']].<ref name=vogue>{{cite journal|url=http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/071404/page2.html|title=Jenna and Barbara Bush: Sister Act|author=Julia Reed|journal=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=August 2004|deadurl=yes|format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AJenna+and+Barbara+Bush%3A+Sister+Act&as_publication=%5B%5BVogue+%28magazine%29%7CVogue%5D%5D&as_ylo=2004&as_yhi=2004&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051220131812/http://www.style.com/vogue/feature/071404/page2.html |archivedate=December 20, 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=July 16, 2004|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-bush-twins-coming-out-party/|title=The Bush Twins' Coming Out Party|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Bush joined her mother on diplomatic trips to [[Liberia]] in January 2006 to attend the inauguration of President [[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.star-telegram.com/living/family/moms/article3829705.html|author=Sandra Baker|date=December 9, 2011|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]] |title=Three companies honored as top workplaces for women in Fort Worth|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> and to [[Vatican City]] to meet with [[Pope Benedict XVI]] in February 2006.
Unlike most of her relatives (but like her twin sister Jenna), Bush is not a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. In 2010, Jenna Bush Hager and Barbara Bush told ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' that they preferred not to identify with any political party, stating, "We're both very independent thinkers."<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://people.com/archive/the-bush-twins-on-their-own-vol-73-no-19/|title=The Bush Twins On Their Own|author=Sobieraj Westfall, Sandra|publisher=People Magazine|date=May 17, 2010|volume=73|number=19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/george-w-bushs-daughters-are-not-republicans-2014-9|title=George W. Bush's Daughters Are Not Republicans|author=Campbell, Colin|work=Business Insider|date=September 4, 2014|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/sep/5/bush-daughters-decline-republican-label-were-both-/|title=Bush daughters decline Republican label: ‘We’re both very independent’|author=Chumley, Cheryl K.|publisher=The Washington Times|date=September 5, 2014|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref>
